title: Weapon - Victorian Knuckle Sliced to Print

description.text: I liked this thing very much but my attempts to print it with support were far from desirous.  So I sliced it in half to print without support.

Print both halves glue together.  It's a nice decorative piece or paper weight.
I printed the first half with 0 shells and it came out with voids.  The second half I printed with 2 shells and it still had voids so I'm not sure what is going on.  However, when both halves are glued together they seem fairly strong for a paper weight.

comments.text: Up scaled mine to fit my hand and fits nicely. I'm sure it could seriously harm someone. Law enforcement should be more concerned about things like these as apposed to 3D printed guns.

description.text: This is a somewhat parametric draw-latch.  Used to hold things shut.  It works on a cam principle and has quite a bit of holding force.

This is somewhat parametric.  I didn't test too many sizes or anything so not sure how the various settings at the top of the scad file will effect things.  After I printed it out I added a "give" parameter which should make the latch easier to close.
If you want to add a latch to your project, you would add the "catch" and "base" parts to your model and then print the "cam" and "latch" seperately.
They pin together and work very well.  If you use the non +give stl file you will have no play once the latch is closed.  I didn't try it, but using filament for your pins may actually work really well since it would add elasticity.

comments.text: Downloaded this and used it on a prototype for a carrying case. I love the design, but if you add a bevel to it, everything gets better. The clearances are smoother, the edges are smoother, and everything just works smoother. I also personally opened the holes up on the inner pieces a bit, just so it moves more freely right away. One adjustment I realized might help after a bit of use is an alignment notch of some sort.
comments.author: DC010

title: Z End Stop Adjustment - Thumb Screw

description.text: I made this to be used with my end stop adjuster (thing:15270) so that I could adjust the end stop from above.  I'm sure it could be used for many other things.  The design was based around a 6-32 nut however you may be able to scale it a bit in meshlab to fit an M4.

1) Print STL.
2) Drink beer while printing.
3) Press 6-32 nut in the nut recess.
4) Screw your 6-32 machine screw down through the open circular recess.
You may need to use two additional nuts to pinch the threads to help screw.
5) Run a 6-32 nut tight to the recessed nut.
Make this fairly tight to prevent the thumbscrew adapter from backing out.
6) Drink more beer.
